\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a parametric model 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ p(y;\theta)\mid\theta\in\Theta\right\} $
\end_inset

 and a sample 
\begin_inset Formula $\cd=\left\{ y_{1},\ldots,y_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
likelihood 
\series default
of parameter estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}\in\Theta$
\end_inset

 for sample 
\begin_inset Formula $\cd$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(\cd;\hat{\theta})\pause=\prod_{i=1}^{n}p(y_{i};\hat{\theta}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Pause

\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In practice, we prefer to work with the 
\series bold
log-likelihood
\series default
.
 Same maximum but
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log p(\cd;\hat{\theta})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\log p(y_{i};\theta),
\]

\end_inset

and sums are easier to work with than products.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
